{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_broadwick_ver01/data/sn93065779/00279558236/1945092701/0397.xml":{"full_text":"LmuOm cuuinty-8 FAVORITE FAMILY NEWSPAFEB\nLabor Unrest Perils\nReconversion Program\nGovernment\u2019s Stabilization\nPolicy Facing Big Test;\nStrikes Spreading\nAlready well under way, the great\ntask of reconversion, with its prom\nise of full employment ir. postwar\nAmerica, has been threatened with\ndelay by impending strikes in major\nW industries of the nation.\nWith wage increase s heading up\nthe unions\u2019 principal demands, the\ngovernment\u2019s whole stabilization pro\ngram for the transitional period to\nnormal peacetime production hangs\nin the balance. In an effort to hold\ndown costs until supply begins to\ncounter-balance demand, the adminis\ntration has decreed the maintenance\nof the 1K42 price level and retained\nbroad wage controls.\nCaught between industry\u2019s reluc\ntance to grant pay increases under\nfixed prices and labor\u2019s insistence\nupon retaining high wages, the gov\nernment was faced with a first rate\neconomic problem with far-reaching\npolitical implications. Having de\nclared that nothing should stand in\nthe way for speedy reconversion,\nPresident Harry S. Truman wa s com\nmitted to solution of what might well\nbecome the most difficult of his do\nmestic tasks.\nThough the United Steel Workers\n(CIO) were to present their demands\nfor a $2 a day raise to the most ba\nsic of America\u2019s heavy industries,\nsupplying the principal material for\na wide variety of durable goods, the\nunrest in the automobile manufactur\ning centers provoked the most imme\ndiate concern\nEven before the United Automo\nbile Workers (CIO) announced their I,\ndetermination to fight for a 30 peri\ncent wage increase by the novel I,\nmeans of production stoppage in the\nbiggest pace-setting company i n thel,\nindustry, Ford laid off 50,000 em-j\nployee s as a result of strikes in the|.\nplants of important subcontractors, j\nIn planning its new bargaining\ntechnique, the UAW singled out the\ngreat General Motors Corporation, j\nsince GM supposedly sets the wage\npattern for the entire automobile in\ndustry. Armed with a $4,000,000 war\nchest, the UAW threatened to halt\nproductiort completely in GM plants\nwhile permitting full-scale output by\ncompetitors. Thus, not only would\nGM see its own market open to in\nvasion by other companies, but it\nI would also be left far behind in tun\ning up production for the race in the\nprosperous postwar period.\nWhile GM reportedly was singled\nout for the so-called \u201cblockade,\u201d the\nCAW preserved its strategic position\nby also preparing to file strike no\ntices against Chrysler and Ford, the\nother two great producers in the in\ndustry.\nAs the powerful UAW maneuvered\nfor a 30 per cent wage increase, the\nequally powerful United Steel Work\ners squared off for a decisive fight\nwith 86 of the industry\u2019s top produc\ners, including the great United States\nSteel Corporation.\nIn asking a $2 daily wage increase,\nthe USW cited the wartime earnings\nSEE\nGOODIN BURRIS FURNITURE COMPANY\nFor Your\nBendix Home Laundry\nDeliveries Will Begin Within 45 Days\nPlace Your Order NOW!\nNotice!\nBeginning Saturday, September 29th\nThe\nCourt House\nWill Close\nEvery Saturday at 3 P. M.\nW. H. Boring,\nClerk to Board of County Commissioners\n11 of the industry, claiming that both\nj so-culled \u201chidden\u201d and declared prof\nits approximated 2-billion dollars\nfor the 1941-\u201945 period. Os the to\ntal, USW said, 800 million dollars\nwere \u201chidden\u201d in the form of accu\nmulated reserves, excess provisions\ni for depreciation and depletion, accel\norated amortization of wartime facil\nities, and large set-asides for pen\nsions.\nCountering the USW demands, in\ndustry officials declared that any\nsubstantial wage increases would\nhave to be met by raising prices,\nwhich, in turn, would affect the cost\nof a wide variety of durable goods\nusing the metal. If the $2 daily were\ngranted, it was said, the expense of\nproducing one ton of steel would\njump $6.\nPacesetter for the industry, U. S.\nSteel Corporation\u2019s present average\nhourly wage rate stands at $1.15,\nwith two out of three workers earn\ning over $1 per hour.\nWhile the development s in the au\ntomobile and steel industries over\nshadowed all other strike threats, the\nUnited Farm Equipment and Metal\nWorkers\u2019 (CIO) demand for a 30 per\ncent wage increase held interest for\nthe all-important agricultural com\nmunity charged with food produc\ntion.\nIn moving on the International\nHarvester Company, John Deere\nCompany, Oliver Company and Allis-\nChalmers Company, the union de\nclared that the profits of the busi\nnesses in wartime made them capa\nble of paying the wage demands with\nout raising prices. At the same time\nthe union announced that it would\nconduct a propaganda campaign\namong farmers to combat company\nclaims that high wages are responsi\nble for the high cost of their machin\nery.\nMeanwhile, the oil industry feared\nI a nation-wide spread of strikes fol\nlowing walkouts at refineries in the\nMiddle West over demands of the Oil\nWorkers union (CIO) for same pay\nfor 40 hours as they had been re\nceiving for 52 hours. As production\nof a vital source -of U. S. power was\nthreatened, company officials coun\ntered with an offer for a 15 per cent\nwage increase for 40 hours.\nWith the government having re\nmoved most production controls, only\nthe difficult labor situation appeared\nto stand in the way of quick recon\nversion. In addition to strike threats,\nmanpower shortages were handicap\nping efforts of the coal, copper and\nbuilding industries\nOn the basis of reports from 14,-\n000 members, the National Associa\ntion of Manufacturers declared that\nprogress of the overall reconversion\neffort appeared excellent, with real\nprosperity ahead for the next two\nor three years at least.\nGREAT FAMILY\n\u201cI am Red Eagle,\u201d said the Indian\nchieftain to his paleface visitor.\n\u201cThis is my son, Fighting Bird.\nAnd here,\u201d he added, \"is my grand\nson, P-38.\u201d\nTHE LINCOLN TIMES, UNCOLKTON, N. C., THURSDAY, SEPT. 27, 1945\nGoodman in Embryo\nThis lone tootler Is Milton Stoloff\nof Atlantic City, N. J., one of Camp\nDeerwood Adirondack\u2019s youngest\nmembers. The camp for music lov\ners, of all ages, provides summer\ninstruction for bands and concerts.\nTourists May\nCircle Globe In\nLess Than Week\nWashington, Sept. 27\u2014Round-the\nworld travel has hit a new high. Soon\nyou will be able to take the Globester\nand go around the world in a mere\nsix and one-quarter day flight. Os\ncourse, you have to take all kinds of\ninnoculations, have plenty of patience\n\u2014and last, but by no means least,\nhave $2,400 for your ticket.\nThe Globester is a \u2019round-the\nworld air service which will be in\naugurated by the Army Air Trans\nport Command tomorrow. Then it\nwill become a regular thing from the\nnational airport, released for civilian\nuse.\nRemember those famous \u2019round\nthe-world flights of the past? In 1924\nfolks thought it was pretty good\nwhen United States Army airplanes\ndid it in 175 days\u2014more than 14j\ndays actual flying time. Then in\n1929 the German dirigible balloon,\nthe Graf Zeppelin made it in 20 days\nand four hours. Wiley Post hit the\nheadlines in 1933 taking his famous\nmonoplane Winnie Mae around the\nnorthern air circumference of the\nworld in little more than seven days.\nYes, and everyone thought that was\nterrific until along came Howard\nHughes. With four assistants,\nHughes made his famous flight in\nrecord time.\nWe can\u2019t help wondering what\nJul6s Verne would have thought of\nit all. The famous French writer\nlived from 1828 to 1905, and how\ndaring and unbelievably out of this\nworld people considered his \u201cAround\nthe World in Eighty Days.\u201d They\ncalled it an original type of highly\nimaginative scientific romance.\nNeed Stenographers\nIn Vet Administration\nBecause of the great need for ste\nnographers to perform vital services\nin the expanding Veterans Adminis\ntration, Washington, D. C., Civil Ser\nvice officials have opened temporary\nappointments to the general public,\nit was disclosed today. These ap\npointments may not exceed one year.\nSaid an official Civil Service\nspokesman, \u201cThe growing number of\ndischarged soldiers has placed an\never increasing burden of responsi\nbility on the Veterans Administra\ntion. The war is not over for the\nveteran\u2014 every, qualified stenogra\npher is urged to apply to help in this\nimportant program.\u201d\nSalaries range from. $1704 to $1902\nper year depending upon the quali\nfying experience of the applicant.\nTo qualify for the $1704 a year\nposition, applicants must only pass\nan appropriate Civil Service test.\nTo qualify for the $1902 a year\nposition, an additional year of full\ntime experience or education above\nhigh school level will be required.\nFurther information may be se\ncured from Miss M. Camp at Lin\ncolnton, N. C., Post Office.\nLicenses Os 11,173\nDrivers Revoked\n803 Date Drive\nRaleigh, Sept. 24\u2014A total of 11,-\n173 automobile drivers have had\ntheir licenses revoked thus far this\nyear for various infractions of the\nhighway regulations, Bodie Ward\nsaid.\nThis year\u2019s total brings to 60,805\nthe number of revocations recorded\nsince the revocation law went into\neffect in 1935, he said.\nOs the total to date this year, 2,678\nwere for driving white drunk. Mean\nwhile, court convictions obtained\nagainst drivers who broke some\nphase of the highway regulations to\ntaled 17.713 thre igh August 30. Os\nthese, 8.527 wer\" for speeding, 8,331\nwere for failing to have drivers\u2019 li\ncenses, 2,043 for faulty equipment,\nand 1,047 for improper lights.\n-M.IQM II\nMEATS AND FATS: Red stamps,\nV 2, W 2, X 2, Y\u20192, Z 2, now valid, ex\npire September 30; Al, El, Cl, Dl,\nEl, now valid, expire October 31;\nFI, Gl, HI, Jl, Kl, now valid, ex\npire November 30; 1,1, Ml, Nl, PI,\nQl, now valid, expire December 31;\nRl, SI, Tl, Ul, VI, become valid Oc\ntober 1, expire January 31, 1946. _\nSUGAR: Sugar stamp No. 38, now\nvalid, expire s December 31.\nSHOES: Airplane stamps Nos. 1,\n2,3, 4, now good.\nIf you don\u2019t read the Times you\nare the loser.\nFarm Tours Provide\nLiberal Education\nFarm tours give growers the op\nportunity of gaining a liberal educa\ntion at very small expense. These\ntours also give information that will\nput extra dollars in the farmer\u2019s\npocket, if he takes advantage of the\nthings that he learns on the tours.\nIt is fine to pick up practical bits\nof information from bulletins, maga\nzines, and books but there\u2019s nothing\nlike seeing a job well done under\nfield conditions and learning of the\nsuccess and mistakes in doing the\njob.\nIn every county in North Carolina\nthere are many outstand mg pieces of\nwork that every farmer should study.\nFarm tours are arranged by county\nagents to facilitate the spreading of\nthis information.\nI Under wartime conditions there\nhave been from 15 to 125 farmers\ntaking advantage of these tours.\nWith the country rapidly returning\nto normal, there is no valid reason\nwhy this number should not be in\ncreased to 1,000 farmers, with grow\ners arranged in groups and scheduled\nto make the rounds at different pe\nriods of the day. Traffic directors\nwill need to be appointed.\nThe farmers who have been taking\npart in these tours are the progres\nsive, wide-awake men who are al\nways on the alert for new ideas that\nwill enable them to do a job with less\nlabor and expense, and for informa\ntion that will put extra dollars in\ntheir pockets. The grower who needs\nthe help most is generally absent\nfrom these meetings\u2014will not walk\nacross the road to find out what it\nis all about. He is the individual\nwho is content to plod along as he\nhas in the past, while new idea s and\nnew practices sweep past him.\nHere\u2019s a job for neighborhood farm\nleaders. Get these me n out to farm\nmeetings and get them interested in\nfarm tours.\nFarmers Save Feed\nBy Building Silos\nMany North Carolina fanners, es\npecially dairymen and beef cattle\ngrowers, are now building silos to\nround out a complete program of\nfeed production.\nMecklenburg County farmers have\nbeen using a set of silo forms pur\nchased by county officials to excel\nlent advantage. Stanly county, real\nizing that it is rapidly becoming a\nlivestock section, has also bought a\nset of silo farms for its dairymen\nand beef cattle men. Assistant Agent\nV. A. Huneycutt of the State Exten\nsion Service says that this is one of\nthe best investments Stanly County\never made because it enuble s farm\ners to build silos at a greatly re\nduced cost.\nRecently a group of farmers from\nLenoir visited dairymen in Wake.\nThey found that Dave Worth had\nfilled two silos from 10 acre s with\nabout 125 tons of silage.\nWhen they visited W. V. Green\nand asked about silos, ho said: \u201cThe\nwind blew down my silo and I am in\ndoubt as to whether I should build\nanother or not. I am waiting to see\njust how much feed I can produce\nwith good permanent pastures and\nsupplemental grazing crops, both\nwinter and summer. Just now I am\n\u2018on the fence\u2019 a s to this matter of\nputting up a silo.\u201d\nW. B. Franks said that he did not\nneed a silo because he is specializing\non permanent pastures, supplemental\ngrazing crops, and alfalfa. He has\n85 acres of permanent pasture. Ho\nobtained 3 months of grazing for 55\ncows from 21 acres of supplemental\ngrazing crops of rye grass and crim\nson clover. He seeded lespedeza on\n\u201cRelax\u201d is the word... Have a Coke\n...or making a rest refreshing \u00a33\nWartime tension and overtime work make relaxation doubly important. B||sfppljpKs2S|B\nWhether fishing or spending Sunday on your own porch, there\u2019s nothing\nlike ice-cold Coca'Cola to make a brief rest refreshing. Keep Coca-Cola\nin your refrigerator at home. Have a Culp is the invitation to enjoy\nthe pause that refreshes. \u2018\u2018Coke\u2019\u2019-Coca-Cola\nBOTTLED UNDER AUTHORITY OF THE COCA-COLA COMPANY BY called by its friendly abbreviation\nLincolnton Coca-Cola Bottling Company. uct of The eoca-Cou company.\nQIV4S Tho C-C\nA Parable About\n\u201cColonel Hooker\u201d\n(Published by Request)\nNow there lived in a certain Com\nmunity a Man known fpr and wide\na s Colonel Hooker. And he lived in\na great house. And he had much\nWealth. Howbeit, no Man knew how\nhe became a Colonel. And None in\nquired. For Colonel Hooker was a\ngreat Man.\nAnd Colonel Hooker had a Reputa\ntion for tarrying long at the Wine.\nHowbeit, Wine was not its real Name.\nFor he took his straight. And its\nreal Name was Whisky.\nAnd Colonel Hooker prided himself\non his Ability to take much W\u2019hisky\nwithout staggering in his W\u2019alk. And\nif perchance he did stagger just a\nBit, Colonel Hooker laughed and said,\nThis is my Swagger; thi s i s the Way\nI prefer to walk. And no Man ar\ngued with him. For he was a great\nMan.\nNow once upon a Night Colonel\nHooker tarried longer than usual at\nthe Tavern. And when he arose to\ngo Home, behold, he staggered much.\nAnd when he came unto the Road\nthat led to his great House, he had\nmuch Difficulty in finding the Way.\nAnd he wandered from the Road and\ninto a Field.\nNow there was a Mudhole in the\nField. And because the Night was\nwarm, a Hog had gone into the Mud\nhole to cool his Hide. And Colonel\nHooker fell into the Mudhole. How\nbeit, the Hog was not much disturb\ned.\nAnd when Colonel Hooker came to\nhimself, behold, he was in the Com- l\npany of a Hog. And he liked it not.\nFor the Hog and the Mudhole were\nStench unto his Nostrils.\nAnd Colonel Hooker made much\nEffort to arise. And when he had\nsucceeded in sitting up (howbeit, he\nwas still sitting i n the Mudhole), he\nsaid unto the Hog, Hog thou art;\nand Hog thou wilt always be. But\nI am a Man. And I belong not\namong the Hogs. I will arise and go\nto my House, and I will never again\ndrink that which companieth me with\nthe^Hogs.\nAnd he arose. And he came unto\nhis House. And he washed himself.\nAnd he became a Man. And he drank\nno more Bourbon.\nNow I know that this Parable will\ngive Offense unto many who drink\nbut drink not to Excess. But I say\nunto Such, behold, thou takest dan\ngerous Stuff when thou drinkest.\nAnd although thy Drinking may not\nput thee into the Mudhole where wal-\nlow the Hogs, yet it putteth thee into\nthe Company of those who do fall\ninto the Gutter.\nAnd if thou wouldst be a Help\nunto thy Fellow Man, let Liquor\nalone. For Many there be who fall\ninto grievous Ways when they look\non the Liquor that sparkleth.\nBut \u201cat the last it biteth like a\nSerpent.\u201d\nthe grazing crop in early spring and\nrecently cut 725 bales of lespedeza\nhay, averaging 79 pounds each from\nthe 21 acres. The land is now back\nto rye grass and crimson clover and\nFrank s says: \u201cYou can\u2019t beat this\nsystem.\u201d\nDELICIOUS RECIPES FOR\nPREPARING OYSTERS\nA collection of recipes and helpful\nsuggestions for preparing appetizing\noysters. Also many other hints to\naid housewives planning menus. Look\nfor these features in the October 7th\nissue of\nTHE AMERICAN WEEKLY\nNation\u2019s Favorite Magazine With The\nBALTIMORE SUNDAY AMERICAN\u2019!\nOrder from Your Local Newsdealer;\ndKgpme...\nAUantujOompany B\u2019rufTits in^ratUa^CHajlollt, C*allarux>ia~Xo?to!k Orlando\nDr. Aubrey L. Palmer\nCh&rlotte Optometrist\nIn Lincolnton each Thursday 9 a. m. to 5 p. m.\nLincolnton Office\u2014\nCharlotte Office\u2014\nEYES EXAMINED GLASSES FITTED\nAUCTION SALE\nAt My Home Place, 5 Miles West of Lincolnton, on\nSaturday, September 29, at 2 O\u2019Clock\nI will offer for sale my entire stock of farming tools,\n1 sewing machine and other household articles.\nJ. S. Scronce,\nRoute 1, Lincolnton, N. C.\nN _ ow A New Engine\nJllllli evro e\nWe can replace your worn-out, gas-wasting en\ngine with a new complete cylinder block and\nworking parts\u2014factory-assembled.\nHERE\u2019S WHAT YOU GET:\nNew cylinder block New pistons and\nNew crankshaft rings\nNew camshaft New connecting rods\nNew timing gears New front-end plate\nIn short, every important part that operates to\ndevelop power is brand-new just as in your\noriginal engine.\nHere is the answer to your transportation\nproblem.\nPolhill Chevrolet Co.\nCourt Square Phone 344 Lincolnton, N. C.\nPAGE THREE","height":"20655","width":"15071"}}
